'''Blagodatnoye Nebo Icon of the Mother of God''' (Икона Пресвятой Богородицы «Благодатное Небо») — a revered {{ill|icon|ru|икона|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Mother of God|ru|Богородица|qq=draft}}, traditionally brought to {{ill|Moscow|ru|Москва|qq=draft}} from {{ill|Lithuania|ru|Великое княжество Литовское|qq=draft}} by {{ill|Sophia Vitovtovna|ru|Софья Витовтовна|qq=draft}}, the wife of Grand Prince {{ill|Vasily I of Moscow|ru|Василий I Дмитриевич|qq=draft}}. The icon was previously kept in {{ill|Smolensk|ru|Смоленск|qq=draft}}<ref>{{ill|Singayevsky V.|ru|Сингаевский В.|qq=draft}} *Famous Russian Icons*. — M.: Astrel, 2010 — ISBN 978-5-271-26497-9 — p. 69</ref>. The name derives from the Marian hymn of the First Hour: “What shall we call you, O Full of Grace? Heaven, for you have shone forth the Sun of Righteousness.”

== History and Venerated Copies ==
In 1678–1680, the {{ill|Armory Chamber|ru|Оружейная палата|qq=draft}} iconographers created a copy for the {{ill|Archangel Cathedral (Moscow Kremlin)|ru|Архангельский собор (Москва)|qq=draft}}. In 1682, master {{ill|Vasily Poznansky|ru|Познанский, Василий|qq=draft}} produced an applique version for the {{ill|Church of the Exaltation of the Cross (Terem Palace)|ru|Крестовоздвиженская церковь (Московский Кремль)|qq=draft}}.

The icon depicts the {{ill|Vision of the Woman Clothed with the Sun|ru|Жена, облечённая в солнце|qq=draft}} from the Revelation of {{ill|John the Theologian|ru|Иоанн Богослов|qq=draft}}. The Mother of God stands full-length with the Christ Child on her left arm, surrounded by a solar {{ill|mandorla|ru|мандорла|qq=draft}}, with a crescent moon under her feet. Crowns adorn their heads.

The feast day is {{СС|19|March||6}} and also celebrated on the {{ill|Sunday of All Saints|ru|Неделя всех святых|qq=draft}}.

Local venerated copies are kept in the {{ill|Church of the Trinity on Vorobyovy Hills|ru|Храм Троицы Живоначальной на Воробьёвых горах|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Menshikov Tower|ru|Меншикова башня|qq=draft}} in Moscow.

Believers pray to the Blagodatnoye Nebo Icon for healing from illnesses and for guidance of those living unrighteous lives toward the Christian faith. Some refer to the icon by the hymn’s phrase “What shall we call you.” The icon holds special veneration in Moscow, long housed in the Archangel Cathedral.
